In the first code:

```java
public class Kata {
    public static int squareSum(int[] n) {
        int sum = 0;
        for (int i : n) {
            sum += n[i] * n[i];
        }
        return sum;
    }
}
```

You are **using the values as index**, so the iterations will be:

 1. `i = 1` -&gt; `n[i] = 2`
 2. `i = 2` -&gt; `n[i] = 2`
 3. `i = 2` -&gt; `n[i] = 2`

In the second code:

```java
public class Kata {
    public static int squareSum(int[] n) {
        int sum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n.length; i++) {
            sum += n[i] * n[i];
        }
        return sum;
    }
}
```

Works because you are **correctly iterating over the indexes**, so the iterations will be:

 1. `i = 0` -&gt; `n[i] = 1`
 2. `i = 1` -&gt; `n[i] = 2`
 3. `i = 2` -&gt; `n[i] = 2`

If you want to use a *For-Each Loop*, you can do it this way:

```java
public class Kata {
	public static int squareSum(int[] n) {
		int sum = 0;
		for (int value : n) {
			sum += value * value;
		}
		return sum;
	}
}
```

### Edit:

In [your answer][1] you asked:

&gt; why the result of wrong code is 12 instead of exception?

Well, you have the list `{1,2,2}`, so the indexes will be:

 - Index: `0` -&gt; Value: `1`
 - Index: `1` -&gt; Value: `2`
 - Index: `2` -&gt; Value: `2`

It don&#39;t throw an exception because the array actually have the indexes `1`, `2` and `2`. 

But if you use `{1,2,3}`, it will throw a `java.lang.ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` because the array don&#39;t have the index `3`.

  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/77362247/21144042

&gt; _&quot;Why foreach loop gives the wrong sum in this situation? ...&quot;_

Use _i_, not _n[i]_.

```java
int sum = 0;
for (int i : n) sum += i * i;
return sum;
```

Or, use a _[stream](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/collections/streams/index.html)_.

```java
return IntStream.of(n).map(x -&gt; x * x).sum();
```

```java
return IntStream.of(n).reduce((a, b) -&gt; a + (b * b)).getAsInt();
```

